# -- Graph Publishing / Sveltia CMS (F27) ---------------------------------------
# Model a website directly in the graph — pages as connected nodes — and publish
# a static, graph-powered site. Competes with markdown docs tools (Docusaurus/
# MkDocs/GitBook) but powered by the triple framework and offline for authoring.
# Graph-first: graph is source of truth -> export markdown+frontmatter to content/
# in THIS repo -> Sveltia CMS (external, un-forked) edits -> a /docs route group in
# the main app renders the pages (prerendered via adapter-static) -> Cloudflare
# Pages. Hosting: served alongside the app at Reckons.AI/docs now; a docs.reckons.ai
# subdomain can point at the same /docs build later. See plan "Sveltia CMS Publishing".

kb:graph-publishing rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Graph Publishing (Sveltia CMS)" ;
               kpred:has-status   "in-progress" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F27" ;
               kpred:description  "Publish WebPage graph nodes as a static, graph-powered docs site served at Reckons.AI/docs (self-contained, in the main app — not a separate repo). Graph-first: nodes export to content/<section>/<slug>.md (frontmatter + body) plus graph.json; Sveltia CMS (external bundle, un-forked) edits the files; a prerendered /docs route group renders them via mdsvex; Cloudflare Pages deploys. Hybrid body: excerpt in graph, long-form markdown in Git. Offline-capable authoring and .zip export. Future: docs.reckons.ai subdomain over the same build." ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:gp-phase-1 ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:gp-phase-2 ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:gp-phase-3 ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:gp-phase-4 ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:knowledge-graph ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:repo-ingest ;
               kpred:hosting      "Served at Reckons.AI/docs (route group in the main app, prerendered via adapter-static). Future: docs.reckons.ai subdomain over the same /docs build." ;
               kpred:principle    "Graph/TTL + Reckoning is the PRIMARY authoring surface. AI-generated page content is directly editable in the graph; content/*.md is a generated, trailing by-product. Sveltia editing is a secondary convenience (round-trips back into the graph)." ;
               kpred:principle    "A markdown alignment check keeps content/*.md honest against the graph: CI regenerates markdown from the WebPage nodes and flags any committed .md that drifts (edited outside the graph, or graph changed without re-publish) — mirroring the Reckons.AI Graph Alignment Check." ;
               kpred:principle    "The docs knowledge graphs (static/starter-guide.ttl + static/docs-*.ttl) are the source of truth for the 'generated' /docs sections; Sveltia CMS is for the OTHER content (releases) and for capturing refinements back into the graph, not for hand-editing generated pages — see kb:docs-pipeline." ;
               kpred:supports     "Embeddable images (Sveltia media_folder) and the rest of Sveltia's CMS widgets remain available for hand-editing." ;
               kpred:credits      "Sveltia CMS — github.com/sveltia/sveltia-cms (MIT). Used as an external dependency; consider sponsoring." .

kb:webpage-entity rdf:type   ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "WebPage Entity" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F27.0" ;
               kpred:description  "Dedicated ktype:WebPage entity type with page: metadata (slug, section, template, status, nav, excerpt, body, date). Reuses nav:order for position, skos:broader for the site tree, nav:next/prev for sequence, skos:related for cross-links. src/lib/rdf/page.ts builds an ordered SitePage[]." ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:graph-publishing .

kb:post-template rdf:type    ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Post Template (dated content)" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F27.1" ;
               kpred:description  "A 'post' PageTemplate for dated, reverse-chronological content — release notes, announcements, and blog entries. Adds page:date (urn:reckons:page/date, ISO yyyy-mm-dd literal) alongside the existing page: predicates. src/lib/rdf/page.ts's sitePosts() helper sorts template==='post' pages newest-first within a section (undated posts sort last); other templates keep the general (section, order, title) sort from buildSitePages() untouched. src/routes/docs/_content/docs.ts mirrors the same ordering for the prerendered /docs site: a section made up entirely of posts renders newest-first as a release-notes-style feed (date + excerpt), e.g. content/releases/. Round-trips through site-export.ts/site-import.ts (date: frontmatter, omitted when unset) and Sveltia CMS (config.yml + the generated sveltiaConfig() both offer a 'post' template option and a date widget)." ;
               kpred:use-case     "Release notes — e.g. content/releases/v0-1-0.md, the shipped Reckons.AI v0.1.0 post." ;
               kpred:use-case     "Product announcements." ;
               kpred:use-case     "Blog entries." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:webpage-entity ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:graph-publishing .

kb:gp-phase-1  rdf:type      ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label    "Phase 1 — WebPage model (offline, graph-only)" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:description  "ktype:WebPage type + page: predicates; entity-types registration; isMetaPredicate hides page:* from graph edges; page.ts model. Node-panel authoring affordance pending." ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:graph-publishing .

kb:gp-phase-2  rdf:type      ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label    "Phase 2 — Static export + in-app /docs route" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:description  "src/lib/publish/site-export.ts serializes pages to markdown/frontmatter + graph.json; offline .zip export via fflate. A /docs route group in the main app renders content/*.md via mdsvex, prerendered under adapter-static (hybrid SPA + prerendered /docs). No separate theme repo. Implemented: src/routes/docs/+layout.(ts|svelte) (docs chrome + section nav), src/routes/docs/+page.svelte (index by section), src/routes/docs/[...slug]/+page.(ts|svelte) (per-page renderer with entries() for adapter-static prerendering); content loaded via import.meta.glob('/content/**/*.md', { eager: true }) in src/routes/docs/_content/docs.ts. The rest of the app was moved into a src/routes/(app)/ route group so it keeps its existing SPA-fallback behaviour untouched." ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:gp-phase-1 .

kb:gp-phase-3  rdf:type      ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label    "Phase 3 — GitHub publish + Sveltia /admin" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:description  "Sveltia /admin now shipped in the app (static/admin/index.html + config.yml, external CDN bundle) and served at Reckons.AI/admin; a starter content/docs/welcome.md seeds the collection. publishSiteToGitHub PUTs content/ to this repo (reuses parseRepoUrl + githubToken). src/lib/publish/site-import.ts round-trips content/<section>/<slug>.md back into WebPage statements (skos:broader/related, reconstructed nav:next/prev). scripts/md-align.ts (npm run md-align) regenerates content/*.md via the round trip and flags drift; wired as a non-blocking step in .github/workflows/kb-watch.yml. Remaining: deploy the GitHub OAuth App credentials for sveltia-cms-auth (manual, one-time)." ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:has-setup    kb:sveltia-cms-setup ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:gp-phase-2 .

kb:gp-phase-4  rdf:type      ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label    "Phase 4 — Graph-powered site features" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:description  "Interactive graph view on the published site (from graph.json), search, related pages, prev/next — the differentiation vs plain markdown docs tools." ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:gp-phase-3 .

kb:docs-pipeline rdf:type    ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Docs KB Publishing Pipeline" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F27.2" ;
               kpred:description  "The docs knowledge graphs (static/starter-guide.ttl, the hub with hnav:order-sequenced leap nodes, plus the nine static/docs-*.ttl sub-graphs: triples-rdf, llm, use-cases, features, integrations-tech, tips-security, timeline-ecosystem, architecture, testing) are the source of truth for the 'generated' sections of the published /docs site. scripts/docs-pages.ts (npm run docs:pages) parses the TTLs with n3, turns each qualifying entity (any subject typed under urn:kbase:type/, excluding each sub-graph's urn:reckons:docs/nav/ back-to-hub stub) into a WebPage, and writes content/<section>/<slug>.md via pageToMarkdown — so the output round-trips through scripts/md-align.ts exactly like Sveltia-authored pages. Every generated page carries generated: \"docs-kb\" in its frontmatter (page:generated / PAGE_GENERATED in src/lib/rdf/page.ts); regeneration is idempotent and prunes any previously-generated file whose entity was removed from the TTLs, but never touches a file without that tag. An entity asserted in both the hub (a lightweight 'summary' stub, kept inline for the hub's own story/graph view) and a sub-graph (the fuller definition) is owned by the sub-graph; slugs are disambiguated by section suffix when two distinct entities share a local name across sections. Generated ~236 pages across 10 sections on first run." ;
               kpred:tooling      "CI (.github/workflows/kb-watch.yml) runs scripts/docs-pages.ts on every push/PR: pushes to main that produce a diff are committed back as github-actions[bot] ('docs: regenerate content from docs KBs'); PRs only report the drift in the job summary. The generator's own idempotency is the loop guard — a regeneration commit produces zero further diff, so it doesn't retrigger itself." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:webpage-entity ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:graph-publishing .

kb:gp-authoring rdf:type     ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label    "Docs authoring surface" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:description  "Website/docs settings live on the Graph page (the manage/switch surface). Reckoning (Situation-Target-Proposal) is a first-class way to draft/edit page content; AI-generated content is directly editable in the graph before it becomes a page." ;
               kpred:decision     "No markdown-to-TTL back-propagation (decided 2026-07-03). Graph edits happen in the app or directly on the TTL files via the local workspace folder linked in Graph settings; Sveltia is only for non-generated content. Edits to generated pages are overwritten by the next regeneration — by design." ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" .

kb:sveltia-cms-setup rdf:type ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label    "Sveltia CMS — Setup (GitHub OAuth)" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:description  "Wire the /admin content manager. The CMS entry (static/admin/index.html) + config (static/admin/config.yml) ship in the app and are served at Reckons.AI/admin. GitHub login uses sveltia-cms-auth, a small Cloudflare Worker." ;
               kpred:setup-step   "1. Deploy sveltia-cms-auth: github.com/sveltia/sveltia-cms-auth (Cloudflare Worker reckons-sveltia-cms-auth, mapped to admin.reckons.ai). DONE." ;
               kpred:setup-step   "2. Create a GitHub OAuth App: Settings > Developer settings > OAuth Apps. Homepage https://reckons.ai; Authorization callback URL https://admin.reckons.ai/callback. MANUAL — a human must do this in the GitHub UI." ;
               kpred:setup-step   "3. Set the worker's GITHUB_CLIENT_ID / GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET vars (and ALLOWED_DOMAINS=reckons.ai) to the OAuth App credentials. TOOLED — paste the OAuth App's Client ID/Secret into SVELTIA_GITHUB_CLIENT_ID / SVELTIA_GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET / SVELTIA_ALLOWED_DOMAINS in .env (see .env.example), then run scripts/sveltia-auth-secrets.sh, which pushes them to the worker via `wrangler secret put`." ;
               kpred:setup-step   "4. backend.base_url in static/admin/config.yml points at https://admin.reckons.ai. DONE." ;
               kpred:setup-step   "5. Visit https://reckons.ai/admin/ and Login with GitHub" ;
               kpred:alt          "Local editing without the worker: Sveltia has no proxy-server backend (@sveltia/cms-proxy-server does not exist on npm) and ignores local_backend (a Decap-only option). On localhost it auto-offers \"Work with Local Repository\" (File System Access API, Chromium-family browsers only) with no config change needed." ;
               kpred:note         "/admin is a standalone static page, so the app's strict CSP does not apply; Sveltia reaches api.github.com and the worker directly." ;
               kpred:note         "RESOLVED (2026-07-02): the earlier bare-404 readiness finding was a missing route — the worker was deployed with the correct sveltia-cms-auth code but had workers.dev previews disabled and no custom domain attached. Fixed by attaching admin.reckons.ai as a Workers custom domain via the Cloudflare API (PUT /accounts/{id}/workers/domains). OAuth App credentials pushed via scripts/sveltia-auth-secrets.sh. Verified: GET /auth?provider=github&site_id=reckons.ai returns 302 to github.com/login/oauth/authorize. Setup steps 1-4 complete; only step 5 (login smoke test at reckons.ai/admin/) remains." ;
               kpred:note         "static/admin/index.html now loads a version-pinned Sveltia bundle (@sveltia/cms@0.169.1) instead of an unpinned \"latest\" CDN URL, so upgrades are deliberate. static/media/ (config.yml media_folder) was missing and has been created with a .gitkeep." ;
               kpred:note         "RESOLVED (2026-07-02): Pages collection listed zero entries after login, even though content/docs/welcome.md and content/releases/v0-1-0.md exist on main with matching frontmatter. Root cause: Sveltia CMS does not implement Decap/Netlify's `nested` collection option at all (confirmed against the pinned @sveltia/cms@0.169.1 bundle and its docs — nested collections are tracked for a future 2.0 release). The committed config's `nested: { depth: 4 }` was silently ignored, so the folder collection fell back to scanning only the immediate content/ directory and found nothing, since both pages live one level down (content/docs/, content/releases/). Fix: replaced `nested: { depth: 4 }` with `path: '{{fields.section | slugify}}/{{fields.slug}}'` in static/admin/config.yml and in the generated-config string sveltiaConfig() in src/lib/publish/site-export.ts (kept in lockstep). `path` is the option Sveltia does support for subfoldered entries: it recursively discovers existing files matching the template and places new ones, with no per-entry index file required. The `slugify` filter mirrors contentPath()'s `slugify(page.section)` so the folder segment matches what's on disk (e.g. section \"Docs\" -> content/docs/). Verified against the real pinned Sveltia bundle via Playwright + the CMS's built-in `test-repo` backend (OPFS-backed, no GitHub auth needed): with the original `nested` config the console logged \"Nested collections are not yet supported in Sveltia CMS\" and the collection showed 0 entries on the exact same seeded files; with the `path` fix it showed 2 entries (Welcome, Reckons.AI v0.1.0) with correct titles/status. Also verified creating a new page (title \"Test Page\", section \"Sandbox\") through the real CMS UI wrote content/sandbox/test-page.md, matching site-export.ts's contentPath() layout exactly. Note: Sveltia's own frontmatter serialization (quoting style, empty-string fields) differs cosmetically from pageToMarkdown()'s canonical form, so scripts/md-align.ts correctly flags freshly CMS-saved files as drifted until they are re-exported from the graph — this is by design, not a bug." .

