# ==============================================================================
# Story: Product Vision & Roadmap Tour
# ==============================================================================

story:roadmap-tour  rdf:type         story:Story ;
                    rdfs:label       "Product Vision & Roadmap" ;
                    story:description "Walk through the design intent and planned features of Reckons.AI." ;
                    story:autoplay   "false" ;
                    story:pace       "12" .

# Step 1: Vision
story:rm-step-1  rdf:type         story:Step ;
                 story:partOf     story:roadmap-tour ;
                 story:order      "1"^^xsd:integer ;
                 story:title      "The Vision" ;
                 story:content    "Reckons.AI is a personal knowledge graph that extracts semantic triples from anything you feed it -- notes, URLs, documents, repos, calendars. It runs entirely in your browser with zero cloud dependency. Knowledge stays local, private, and under your control." ;
                 story:highlight  kb:reckons-ai .

# Step 2: Core Workflow
story:rm-step-2  rdf:type         story:Step ;
                 story:partOf     story:roadmap-tour ;
                 story:order      "2"^^xsd:integer ;
                 story:title      "The Core Loop" ;
                 story:content    "Five workflows form the backbone: Ingest (add knowledge), Review (curate with human-in-the-loop), Explore (navigate the graph), Compare (semantic diffs), and Reckon (AI-powered reasoning). Every triple passes through review before entering your confirmed KB." ;
                 story:highlight  kb:wf-ingest ;
                 story:highlight  kb:wf-review ;
                 story:highlight  kb:wf-explore ;
                 story:highlight  kb:wf-compare ;
                 story:highlight  kb:wf-reckon .

# Step 3: Local-First AI
story:rm-step-3  rdf:type         story:Step ;
                 story:partOf     story:roadmap-tour ;
                 story:order      "3"^^xsd:integer ;
                 story:title      "Local-First AI" ;
                 story:content    "Nine LLM backends range from fully in-browser (WASM, Chrome AI) to local server (Ollama) to cloud (Claude, OpenAI, Gemini, OpenRouter). Per-task overrides let you use a fast local model for chat but a powerful cloud model for extraction. The WASM backend auto-falls back when no API key is set." ;
                 story:highlight  kb:llm-design ;
                 story:highlight  kb:backend-wasm ;
                 story:highlight  kb:backend-ollama .

# Step 4: Extension & MCP
story:rm-step-4  rdf:type         story:Step ;
                 story:partOf     story:roadmap-tour ;
                 story:order      "4"^^xsd:integer ;
                 story:title      "Beyond the Browser Tab" ;
                 story:content    "The browser extension adds research session accumulation across tabs. The MCP server lets AI agents like Claude Code search, query, and add to your KB. Together, they make Reckons.AI a knowledge backbone that other tools can tap into." ;
                 story:highlight  kb:browser-extension ;
                 story:highlight  kb:mcp-server ;
                 story:question   "Want to see what the MCP server can do?" .

# Step 5: Sharing Roadmap
story:rm-step-5  rdf:type         story:Step ;
                 story:partOf     story:roadmap-tour ;
                 story:order      "5"^^xsd:integer ;
                 story:title      "Sharing & Collaboration (Planned)" ;
                 story:content    "The sharing roadmap progresses through three stages: F2 publishes KBs to GitHub Gist as static TTL files. F3 adds read-only guest views with a Fork button. F4 enables collaborative KBs where guests can propose statements. TTL is the protocol -- no accounts required." ;
                 story:highlight  kb:kb-publication ;
                 story:highlight  kb:read-only-guest ;
                 story:highlight  kb:collaborative-kb .

# Step 6: Model Training
story:rm-step-6  rdf:type         story:Step ;
                 story:partOf     story:roadmap-tour ;
                 story:order      "6"^^xsd:integer ;
                 story:title      "Personalized AI (F13)" ;
                 story:content    "The most ambitious planned feature: fine-tune a local model on your KB data. Phase 1 exports training pairs (JSONL). Phase 2 integrates cloud fine-tuning. Phase 3 enables local LoRA adapter training via WebGPU. Your KB teaches the model your domain vocabulary." ;
                 story:highlight  kb:model-training ;
                 story:highlight  train:phase-1 ;
                 story:highlight  train:phase-3 .

# Step 7: Cross-KB Alignment
story:rm-step-7  rdf:type         story:Step ;
                 story:partOf     story:roadmap-tour ;
                 story:order      "7"^^xsd:integer ;
                 story:title      "Cross-KB Alignment" ;
                 story:content    "The next frontier: aligning knowledge across multiple KBs. Compare a production status KB against a roadmap KB to see gaps. Each suggested change clearly indicates which KB it targets. This turns Reckons.AI into a tool for tracking vision vs reality." ;
                 story:highlight  kb:cross-kb-alignment ;
                 story:highlight  kb:multi-kb ;
                 story:question   "Ready to compare this roadmap against production status?" .

# Step 8: n8n Cloud Sync
story:rm-step-8  rdf:type         story:Step ;
                 story:partOf     story:roadmap-tour ;
                 story:order      "8"^^xsd:integer ;
                 story:title      "Private Cloud Sync" ;
                 story:content    "n8n provides self-hosted cloud sync with zero SaaS dependency. The Sync Hub stores KB snapshots via webhooks with content-hash deduplication. The Source Monitor watches URLs every 6 hours and queues pending notes when content changes. Private. Personalized. Perfection." ;
                 story:highlight  kb:n8n-cloud-sync ;
                 story:highlight  kb:n8n-sync-hub ;
                 story:highlight  kb:n8n-source-monitor ;
                 story:question   "Interested in how n8n connects to the enterprise roadmap?" .

# Step 9: Enterprise Vision
story:rm-step-9  rdf:type         story:Step ;
                 story:partOf     story:roadmap-tour ;
                 story:order      "9"^^xsd:integer ;
                 story:title      "Enterprise: People · Policy · Procedure" ;
                 story:content    "The enterprise vision structures organizational knowledge around three dimensions. People: RBAC, team KBs, audit trails. Policy: legal and cultural constraints as graph entities with temporal bounds. Procedure: SOPs and decision trees from intent to execution. Authentication is bring-your-own. Delivery is file-based TTL — portable, diffable, no lock-in." ;
                 story:highlight  kb:enterprise-3ps ;
                 story:highlight  kb:ent-people ;
                 story:highlight  kb:ent-policy ;
                 story:highlight  kb:ent-procedure .

# -- MCP Ollama Bridge (Local LLM Offload) --------------------------------------
# Lets MCP clients (e.g. Claude Code sessions) offload bulk LLM work to a
# LOCAL Ollama instance instead of spending cloud/session tokens. Part of the
# broader "local offload" direction for the MCP server — kept as its own
# entity to avoid clobbering any sibling kb:local-offload description.

kb:mcp-ollama-bridge rdf:type    ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "MCP Ollama Bridge" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:local-offload ;
               kpred:description  "Opt-in MCP tools that route bulk extraction, summarization, and page-drafting work to a local Ollama server (native /api/chat, JSON-schema-constrained output) instead of the calling agent's cloud/session tokens. Disabled unless OLLAMA_BASE_URL is set; OLLAMA_MODEL defaults to devstral-small-2:latest. kb_generate_page grounds a prompt in the graph via the same search-subgraph-compress pipeline as kb_compress before drafting a WebPage markdown document (frontmatter + body, mirroring src/lib/publish/site-export.ts's pageToMarkdown field order) -- a proposal only, never written to a KB or file. kb_entity_markdown renders one entity as WebPage markdown deterministically from its triples with no LLM involved, so it works even when OLLAMA_BASE_URL is unset. All four tools return proposals only and never write to a KB, matching the review-first philosophy (ReviewStatus: pending/pending-removal/confirmed/refined/rejected/superseded)." ;
               kpred:has-tool     "kb_local_extract" ;
               kpred:has-tool     "kb_local_summarize" ;
               kpred:has-tool     "kb_generate_page" ;
               kpred:has-tool     "kb_entity_markdown" ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:mcp-server .

# -- Local Offload (parent) ------------------------------------------------------

kb:local-offload rdf:type      ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Local LLM Offload" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:description  "Offload token-heavy LLM work to local models (Ollama) with quality recovered through intelligent instruction. Schema-constrained decoding via Ollama's native /api/chat format parameter plus a compact few-shot extractor prompt for small models (src/lib/integrations/llm/ollama-extract.ts). Measured (2026-07-02, tests/bench/results): llama3.2:3b ingest F1 0.238 baseline -> 0.500 structured (combined 0.657 — the new best local score, surpassing devstral-small-2's 0.649 with a 2GB model); qwen3:4b 0.000 -> 0.263; devstral-small-2 structured ingest 0.486 (its chat leg did not run in that pass). Children: the MCP Ollama bridge and prefer-local routing (settings.preferLocal + VITE_PREFER_LOCAL: chat, diff summary, and merge analysis default to Ollama when reachable — probe cached 60s via src/lib/integrations/llm/prefer-local.ts — with explicit per-task overrides always winning)." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:cost-awareness ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:llm-providers .

# -- Design System (shadcn-svelte) -----------------------------------------------

kb:design-system rdf:type      ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Design System (shadcn-svelte)" ;
               kpred:has-status   "scaffolded" ;
               kpred:description  "shadcn-svelte foundation on Tailwind v4, themed to the Liquid aesthetic. Preflight (Tailwind's CSS reset) is deliberately omitted — src/lib/styles/tailwind.css imports only the theme and utilities layers, so global.css remains the visual source of truth and the app renders unchanged. Every shadcn token is a var() reference into global.css (e.g. --color-primary -> --accent teal); shadcn's neutral 'accent' hover slot is kept inside @theme only, never clobbering the Liquid --accent custom property. Starter components: button, badge, card, separator, skeleton under src/lib/components/ui/. Pilot: the About-footer 'Send feedback' button." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:rebrand-kb-to-graph ;
               kpred:candidate    "P1 Settings forms: unify the three settings pages' inputs/selects/switches on shadcn form controls — the largest consistency win." ;
               kpred:candidate    "P2 Review cards: Card + color-coded status Badge (pending/confirmed/refined/rejected/superseded) across StatementCard, DiffEntry, AlignmentCard." ;
               kpred:candidate    "P3 Loading states: Skeleton placeholders for graph load, extraction progress, and model downloads instead of text spinners." ;
               kpred:candidate    "P4 Toasts: adopt svelte-sonner for tutorial/WASM-fallback/sync notifications, replacing ad-hoc toast implementations." ;
               kpred:candidate    "P5 Menus & dialogs: shared Dialog/DropdownMenu wrappers that respect the app z-index scale (panels=300, NavBar=400, MergeReview=500); NavBar analyze menu first." ;
               kpred:candidate    "P6 Button hierarchy: audit primary (teal) vs outline vs ghost usage on ingest and kb pages for consistent affordance weight." .

# -- F29: Currents — streamed ingest & the Pod view -------------------------------
# Planned 2026-07-02, refined same day. Ocean naming: a "current" is a configured
# recurring stream (RSS/site/topic) attached to a specific graph; "the pod" is the
# graph view mode where arrivals swim in. News is the first use case, not the only
# one (research-tool tracking, topic monitoring). Decisions: n8n-primary crawl with
# browser fallback; in-app graph delivery (no published feed); type gate on NEW
# entity creation only; settings as meta triples in the graph; arrivals always
# pending-review, previewed translucently in the pod.

kb:currents    rdf:type      ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Currents — Streamed Ingest & Pod View" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F29" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:description  "Recurring external content streams (currents) that merge into a graph through the existing add/merge/review spine. Each arrival becomes pending facts: a document/article node plus extracted concept nodes with provenance links. Personalization is the graph itself: headlines ranked by embedding affinity to the graph's entities. The pod is a graph view mode where pending arrivals render translucent and drifting until accepted. Ground News has no official public API (verified 2026-07-02) — speculative; reliable inputs are RSS/Atom, GDELT, keyed news APIs, Open-Meteo for weather context." ;
               kpred:principle    "Add, merge, and review are the base spine — currents never bypass them. Personalization data (location, interests) stays local-first; the VPS only fetches public feeds." ;
               kpred:naming       "Feature/streams: currents. Graph view mode: the pod (whale-themed accents, consistent with Shelly and the Liquid ocean aesthetic). Avoid: feed (overused), crawl (technical)." ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:currents-phase-1 ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:currents-phase-2 ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:currents-phase-3 ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:currents-phase-4 ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:source-refresh ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:n8n-cloud-sync ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:local-offload ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:source-subscription ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:condition-triggers ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:content-safety .

kb:currents-settings rdf:type ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label    "Graph-level currents settings (meta triples)" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:currents ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:description  "Per-graph configuration stored as urn:reckons:meta/currents/* statements in the graph itself — portable with TTL export/import, visible to MCP tools, hidden from graph edges via isMetaPredicate. Holds: the current definitions (source URL/kind/cadence/label), the entity-type gate (enable/disable NEW entity creation per ktype — e.g. a research graph admits only Tool and Concept), and location/interest markers for ranking. Facts attaching to entities already in the graph always flow through (pending review); only new-entity creation is gated." .

kb:currents-phase-1 rdf:type ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label    "F29.1 — Currents model & type gate" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:currents ;
               kpred:description  "Meta-triples settings module (read/write urn:reckons:meta/currents/*), the entity-type gate enforced where stream-originated batches enter addStatements, and the arrival provenance model (article/document node + extracted concepts + derived-from links). Pure model + gate, no UI. SHIPPED 2026-07-02: src/lib/rdf/currents.ts (settings round-trip, isTypeAllowed, applyTypeGate, buildArrivalStatements), origin-aware gate in addStatements (kb.svelte.ts), currents namespace registered in isMetaPredicate; 14 unit tests." .

kb:currents-phase-2 rdf:type ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label    "F29.2 — Fetch: n8n Currents Monitor + browser fallback" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:currents ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:currents-phase-1 ;
               kpred:has-workflow kb:n8n-currents-monitor ;
               kpred:description  "n8n workflow (extends the Source Monitor pattern): scheduled polling of RSS/Atom feeds and watched pages every 30 minutes respecting each current's cadenceMinutes, dedupes items by URL into a data table, app syncs down and pushes arrivals through the type gate. Direct browser fetch fallback (fetchCurrentDirect) for CORS-friendly feeds, with a clear CORS-flavoured error otherwise. Ranking: BGE-small embedding affinity between item text and the graph's top-degree entities; near-duplicate collapse via cosine clustering; content-policy filter drops blocked items pre-rank. SHIPPED 2026-07-03: n8n workflow qb9uPZ8GScAmuUOX (Reckons Currents Monitor) live-tested against https://hnrss.org/frontpage — real items fetched, deduped, and served back via webhook. App side: src/lib/integrations/n8n/currents-sync.ts (registerCurrent, fetchCurrentItems, fetchCurrentDirect, processArrivals — builds the article node only, skips full extraction on the unattended sweep since it's too heavy; deeper extraction stays a manual, on-demand step from the review UI), src/lib/rdf/current-ranking.ts (rankItems, topEntityLabels). settings.n8nBaseUrl added (reused by both F20 cloud sync and F29.2). 26 unit tests (RSS/Atom fixtures, mocked embeddings, mocked fetch, mocked addStatements)." .

kb:currents-phase-3 rdf:type ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label    "F29.3 — The Pod view & settings UI" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:currents ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:currents-phase-1 ;
               kpred:description  "Pod mode in the graph view: pending arrivals render translucent and drifting (reuse the ghost-graph rendering machinery) with accept/dismiss directly on the node; whale-themed accents. Currents settings UI on the graph management page: define currents, toggle entity types, set location. Context blocks: weather via Open-Meteo (free, no key), in-your-state-yesterday via location-filtered items. Daily briefing summarized via prefer-local Ollama. STARTED 2026-07-02: pod toggle (whale chip) on the graph page; arrival nodes (pending-only entities) render translucent with a drift-bob and sky-blue dashed halo in KnowledgeGraph2D. SHIPPED 2026-07-03: accept/dismiss actions on the node panel when pod mode is on and the selected node is an unaccepted arrival (setStatus→confirmed/rejected across all pending statements touching that node) — src/routes/(app)/+page.svelte, with a small additive onarrivalstatus callback exposed from KnowledgeGraph2D.svelte; currents settings UI on the /kb graph-management page — define/edit/remove currents (slug auto-derived from label), kind select (rss/url/topic), cadence, enabled toggle, entity-type gate as toggle chips (registered types from entity-types.svelte.ts; empty = all allowed), and a location field — src/routes/(app)/kb/+page.svelte, persisted via a new replaceCurrentsSettings() helper in src/lib/rdf/currents-persist.ts (diffs against existing urn:reckons:meta/currents/* statements: rejects removed entries, revives identical-but-previously-rejected entries, adds new ones; settings statements stay status confirmed); 6 unit tests on the pure diff function. REFINED 2026-07-04: the floating pod toggle chip was removed from the graph view (user feedback: disliked the button); pod view is now enabled via a '🐋 pod view' toggle in the currents section of the Graph tab (/kb), backed by a per-device localStorage preference (src/lib/stores/pod-view.svelte.ts, podViewEnabled/setPodViewEnabled). The graph view reads the shared store and shows a small read-only '🐋 pod' status indicator (not a button) when on. Rationale: pod is a currents feature, so its controls live with currents settings on the Graph tab. Remaining: context blocks (weather, in-your-state-yesterday) and the daily briefing summary." .

