# -- F31: Local Model Benchmarking & Orchestration -------------------------------

kb:local-model-bench rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Local Model Benchmarking & Orchestration" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F31" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:in-dev       "2026-07-07"^^xsd:date ;
               kpred:tested-by    "tests/visual/run-vlm-gate-bench.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "tests/bench/run-coding-bench.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "tests/bench/run-agentic-bench.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "tests/bench/run-cost-bench.ts" ;
               kpred:description  "Evidence-driven selection of LOCAL models for agent grunt work: keep the strong cloud model (Opus) on the main/orchestration thread and delegate bulk work to local Ollama models via `ollama launch` integrations (claude/opencode/etc.) on a local multi-GPU Ollama host — zero API cost, private. Two reproducible benchmarks pick the right local model per role. (1) VLM visual-gate bench — tests/visual/run-vlm-gate-bench.ts + vlm-golden.ts — scores local vision models as 'does this appear' gates against human-verified screenshot labels (10 images, 48 checks across 7 capability types: toast/mobile/graph/blank/settings/kb/align-tab); the gate score weights recall highest (a miss waves a real regression through — the one intolerable error) plus precision, accuracy, and latency. A cheap local VLM screens every screenshot; only its flags escalate to the expensive reviewer (Opus/Claude Vision). Result: qwen2.5vl:7b selected (94%, 0 misses); granite3.2-vision brittle (44%, 2 misses) despite a perfect 6/6 smoke test — a caution against trusting smoke tests; moondream is prose-only and unusable for yes/no gating. (2) Coding-correctness bench — tests/bench/run-coding-bench.ts + coding-golden.ts — self-contained edit/implement/fix/parse tasks graded by writing the model's code block to a temp dir and running an assert driver via tsx (pass@1 + latency + tokens + output cleanliness). Result: qwen3-coder selected (4/4, fastest full-passer, terse); devstral-small-2 and gpt-oss:20b also 4/4; the large general model nemotron3:33b was the worst coder here (3/4, slowest, ~10x tokens) — reserve big reasoning models for planning, not code grunt work. Operational lesson baked into both harnesses: local models default to very large context windows (up to 128k) which balloon KV-cache VRAM and can crash larger vision runtimes under contention, so the benches pin a small num_ctx (sized to hold one screenshot / prompt) and unload each model between runs. SHIPPED 2026-07-07. Phase 2 SHIPPED 2026-07-07: tool-loop agentic coding bench — tests/bench/run-agentic-bench.ts + agentic-tasks.ts — drives each local model through a real tool-calling loop (list_files/read_file/write_file/run_tests/finish) in a sandbox, measuring pass@1, turns, self-verification, scope discipline, and spiral rate. Result: devstral-small-2 top (0.98, all pass, fewest turns, ~366 tokens), qwen3-coder and gpt-oss:20b also perfect; nemotron3:33b failed a third time (33% pass, spiraled, 6225 tokens, self-verified once) — consistent across all three benches that big reasoning models are wrong for coding/agentic grunt work. Cost bench SHIPPED 2026-07-07: tests/bench/run-cost-bench.ts + cost-golden.ts — compares Opus-token cost of full-system vs Opus-alone on KB-grounded generation, three arms (A0 Opus+raw KB, A1 Opus+kb_compress-style compressed subgraph, A2 local drafts + Opus reviews), inferring $ from live API usage. Result (Opus 4.8, ~$0.48 spend): A1 and A2 both 79% cheaper than A0 at identical 100% quality — the graph compression is the dominant lever (6x fewer input tokens); local delegation adds little on short outputs and pays only when OUTPUT is large (Opus output tokens at $25/Mtok are the expensive ones). Extended 2026-07-07: a long-form (~700-word) generation task confirmed the delegation win — A2 (local writes, Opus reviews/approves) 77% cheaper than A0 vs A1's 66%, because the expensive OUTPUT is generated free locally; and raw context proved LOWER quality here — the full raw KB scored 60% fact-coverage vs 80% for the compressed subgraph (needle-in-haystack). Capacity note: the whole static KB is ~116k tokens — fits comfortably in Opus's 1M window, but feeding it raw costs ~50x more per query than a compressed subgraph and can ground worse; compression is a cost+quality lever, not a capacity workaround. Harness comparison (OpenCode, Qwen Code): both are built for interactive use and their headless local-model paths are immature — OpenCode ships no local-Ollama provider (only ollama-cloud; needs manual provider config), Qwen Code defaults to qwen-oauth cloud — observed opening a browser to chat.qwen.ai for login even in headless -p mode — and even wired neither completed a trivial fix headlessly in 120s via the OpenAI-compatible /v1 path (~13s cold per call), whereas the minimal custom tool-loop and Claude Code complete the same tasks in seconds. Qualitative conclusion (matching hands-on experience): Claude Code's harness has materially lower friction/overhead for local-model agent work; a clean headless pass-rate comparison would need long timeouts and per-tool auth/config work not yet done." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:mcp-server ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:ci-cd-kb-watch .

# -- F32: Partial Facts & Answer-Flow-Back ---------------------------------------

kb:partial-facts rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Partial Facts & Answer-Flow-Back" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F32" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:in-dev       "2026-07-07"^^xsd:date ;
               kpred:description  "Human-in-the-loop completion of the F31 local-orchestration loop. When a local sub-agent is uncertain about the OBJECT of a fact it emits a PARTIAL FACT — subject + predicate known, object left as a loose end — together with its question, instead of guessing or spending Opus tokens to resolve it. In the review screen the reviewer FILLS the object rather than editing a guessed value: a search-while-typing picker over existing entities (reusing the RelationBuilder node-list pattern), or create-new (new entity IRI via labelToIri, or a plain text value). Accept is gated until the object is filled. On confirm the resolved fact flows BACK to the waiting sub-agent via knowledge.answers.jsonl in the workspace, so it can resume — closing the loop. Model: Statement gains optional needsObject + question fields (types.ts); pending JSONL lines may omit `object` (carrying a `question`) to denote a partial fact; drainAndImportPending maps these to needsObject statements; kb entityChoices() supplies the picker; workspace recordAnswer() appends the resolved triple to knowledge.answers.jsonl. UI in DiffEntry.svelte. Depends on F31 (Opus + local sub-agents + kb_add_note questions). SHIPPED 2026-07-07: demonstrated end-to-end — local agent hoisted a partial fact (embedding-model quantization ?), human filled it in the review picker as a new entity, the answer flowed back via knowledge.answers.jsonl, and the waiting agent resumed; two bugs found in testing and fixed (computeDiff crashed on placeholder objects; swipe-accept could confirm an unfilled ?)." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:local-model-bench ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:review-workbench .

# -- F33: Release Pipeline & Branch Alignment ------------------------------------

kb:release-pipeline rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Release Pipeline & Branch Alignment" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F33" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:in-dev       "2026-07-07"^^xsd:date ;
               kpred:description  "Model the release pipeline in the graphs and check branches against it. Three environments with review gates (static/reckons-production.ttl): kb:env-dev (branch dev, DEVELOPER technical review), kb:env-staging (branch staging, STAKEHOLDER business review), kb:env-production (branch main, both approvals; deploys on push). Features carry promotion predicates: kpred:in-dev / kpred:in-staging / kpred:in-production (dated), plus kpred:dev-approved / kpred:stakeholder-approved sign-offs; has-status 'production' implies in-production. scripts/branch-align.ts parses these claims and compares them to real git state (branch existence, main..branch merged PRs), reporting the pipeline per environment and flagging drift: features marked in-dev but status 'production' (contradiction), 'functional' features not marked in any env (untracked), in-dev features already on main (should promote to production status), missing env branches, and merged PRs on a branch not reflected by any tracked feature (unplanned). Run: npm run branch-align. Complements the code<->KB alignment in scripts/kb-align.ts (F26) by adding the environment/branch dimension. Development lifecycle — each gate reviews against a graph: (1) BUSINESS DEFINITION of the feature in the roadmap graph (business-goal level, stakeholder-owned); (2) developer + Opus orchestrate the technical spec in the CODEBASE graph; (3) local agents do the task work; (4) PR to dev; (5) DEVELOPER gate — collaborative review of the dev deploy (dev.reckons-ai.pages.dev) with visual-testing agents (VLM), confirming the implementation against the codebase graph -> kpred:dev-approved; (6) merge to staging; (7) STAKEHOLDER gate — business review on staging.reckons-ai.pages.dev of the built feature against the ORIGINAL roadmap goal (does the result meet the intent) -> kpred:stakeholder-approved; (8) agent-assisted DOCUMENTATION generation, reviewed by the stakeholder; (9) merge to main (production, reckons.ai). Env nodes carry kpred:deploy-url and kpred:reviews-graph (dev->codebase technical spec, staging->roadmap business intent); production requires-documentation." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:ci-cd-kb-watch ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:git-analysis .

kb:deep-testing rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Deep Testing & Living Coverage" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F34" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:description  "An OFFLINE, ever-growing use-case test system distinct from the fast per-build suite. (1) Deep tests are PREDETERMINED end-user PATHS through the web app, run LOCALLY on demand — not on every build; the per-build suite stays fast (unit + smoke). (2) Two evaluation dimensions beyond pass/fail: a VISUAL surface (each path is captured across a DEVICE MATRIX via Playwright device descriptors — phones + tablets: iPhone 15, Pixel 7, iPad Pro 11 are already configured in playwright.config.ts as touch-emulated projects, extensible to more; a local VLM then scores the per-device screenshots against the Web/Mobile UI-UX Rubric, so responsive/touch guidelines are checked at real viewport sizes — scalable emulation that complements spot-checks on physical iPhone/iPad) and a TEXT/output-consumption surface (generated answer/output quality — leads with the conclusion, scannable, grounded). (3) The rubric is a graph: reckons-workspace design-principles KB (kb:web-uiux-rubric) — testable guidelines grounded in core design principles; every finding CITES the violated guideline (kpred:derives-from -> core principle). Mobile-tagged guidelines gate the responsive work. (4) Opus orchestration periodically ANALYSES coverage, finds GAPS, and authors new path specs at various times (not every build); paths are graph entities so the library grows. (5) Novel user workflows: the app transparently benches and KINDLY ASKS the user to opt in to contributing their real workflow as a new test path (consent-based, never covert). (6) Runs as an offline procedure (scripts/offline/), emitting gaps + rubric violations as pending questions for review in Reckons.AI. Builds on visual-testing (VLM gate) and relates to the release pipeline's developer gate. Consumes the offline-first / Opus-orchestrates-online model." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:visual-testing ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:release-pipeline .

kb:steering-committee rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Steering Committee (Enterprise)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F35" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:priority     "low" ;
               kpred:description  "FUTURE / enterprise-only: a group of people vote on a decision (e.g. approving a proposed fact, promotion, or roadmap change). Requires RBAC and bring-your-own authentication provider (SSO/LDAP/OIDC). Votes and outcomes modelled as graph entities. Deprioritised in favour of mobile UI/UX work — noted here so the intent is not lost." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:enterprise-3ps .

kb:mobile-uiux rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Mobile UI/UX Architecture" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F36" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:priority     "high" ;
               kpred:description  "Make Reckons.AI genuinely usable on mobile by fixing how the app uses its UI libraries. DIAGNOSIS (measured 2026-07-07): no shared breakpoint system — 23 hand-rolled @media blocks across ~10 arbitrary px breakpoints (600/640/500/900/380/420...) vs a single Tailwind responsive prefix; Tailwind v4 is installed but its responsive system is effectively unused; no useMediaQuery/viewport store and no @theme screens tokens. SnapPanel is a px-width position:fixed floating window dragged via MOUSE events (clientX/clientY, no touch) that snaps to corners computed from window.innerWidth — unusable on a phone. 18 fixed/absolute floating panels stacked by z-index (300-500) overlap instead of reflowing. bits-ui Dialog/Popover/Select/Tooltip are used as desktop patterns (centre modals, hover tooltips) with no mobile sheet/drawer equivalent. ARCHITECTURE (phased): (1) FOUNDATION — one breakpoint source of truth: Tailwind @theme screens tokens + CSS custom-media + a Svelte 5 viewport rune store (isMobile / isTouch / breakpoint via matchMedia + pointer:coarse). (2) ADAPTIVE PRIMITIVES — a Sheet/Drawer primitive (bits-ui Dialog styled as a bottom sheet) and an AdaptivePanel wrapper that renders SnapPanel on desktop but a bottom sheet / full-screen drawer on mobile; Select -> sheet/native picker on mobile; Tooltip -> tap-to-reveal or dropped on coarse pointers. (3) INPUT — replace SnapPanel mouse-drag with Pointer Events (touch + mouse) and disable free-drag on mobile in favour of the sheet. (4) LAYOUT — single-column reflow below 640px, primary actions in the thumb zone, touch gestures on the 2D/3D graph, >= 44px targets. Verified by F34 deep tests against the mobile-tagged guidelines in kb:web-uiux-rubric (touch-targets, responsive-layout, progressive-disclosure). Prioritised over F35 steering-committee." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:visual-testing ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:deep-testing .

